57110037_2351877908184665_77165340639462.Caption:
There have been times I’ve felt low in life. Where I’ve been tired of people walking away, ending bonds and never looking back. In that moment, I know I cannot really prove a point to keep the persons who matter to me. And alas, I’ll let them go, with their own happy will. 
Why? Because I’ve tried, tried enough to let go off my self respect. Tried enough to hold onto a friendship that never looked destructible until now. 
And here I am, writing my new experiences while holding onto my previous travel journeys with friends who mattered more than anyone.

So I’ll look at this white paradise, I’ll look into this place at an altitude of 9626 ft: - A place away from the voices of the world, where a serene frozen lake awaits to show its splendid mountains, greenery and snow-covered path. - A place, which makes me remember that there’s so much my life have to offer that I need not beg anyone in all my genuine self to stay. - A place, making me realise more about my dreams and the things I should be grateful for. 
With this, I’ve learnt to smile the way I am smiling here in these pictures because this helps me in uplifting myself, without feeling the fear of friendships ending in ways I never thought of.

So what a splendid unplanned trip I was grateful to be a part of.
Thanks Kareri Lake, you’ve been wonderful

@rijulshergill With due regards sir, I’ll like you to review about the ways in which this post might not fit into your “Portraits of wrong” and for also accusing the people who liked this post with a total sense of genuine generosity. This is what you should notice:  1. The surface water of the lake freezes at 32 F. The freezing then spreads downwards into the lake and the ice thickens. So the lake was all densely frozen.  2. Taking the reference of the picture in the post, it’s likely visible with the layers of apparels I’m wearing along with the shoes I’ve put on. There’s no point of hypothetical situations happening anyhow. 3. With this concern of yours, I’ll like to tell you that I’m safe with all my senses and knowledge about what’s wrong and right while on a trek. 4. With people all around the country polluting the sacred rivers of Ganga and Yamuna by bathing, washing clothes, putting garbage and doing toiletries. I don’t believe that me standing on the “frozen lake” could harm the river in any possible way. 5. I’m aware of the fact about how fragile our environment and economy is, and with this due concern, I’ve picked almost every plastic bags and garbage I could find on my way to the top, at this altitude of 9626 ft with a mission to keep my earth green and clean. Also, with the clauses you mentioned, there was absolutely no destruction or damages done. It was with all my genuine respect that I visited this holy place and only cleaned and helped to keep it green - which is the least I could have done. I respect your comment and your concern, but it was highly not acceptable of you accusing the fellow members of the travel community or the locals who showed support for this post. We’re all young people with the perfect sense of how our environment and ecology should be kept safe, without disrupting the norms.

There’s so much that can be done about it, and me going to this Holy lake with a mission of making the surrounding clean and green won’t hurt the sentiments of people. There’s already so much going around in this world, and having said that, I believe me making few steps for the clean and green environment could add to the generosity this world is lacking.
